One thing I wonder about is: Nauty finds the
permutations that you can apply to the entire graph.
But I only care about the "border nodes". Can I
easily "restrict" the group to just these? That would
also reduce the work involved in Frucht's theorem,
which I'm slightly worried about could be large, as
it constructs the entire Cauley graph. This graph,
on a subgraph of Sn could have 2n elements. So it
